<chapter id="introduction">
<title>Introduction</title>

<para>
This handbook is intended to give you an overview of all the functions and ease of use of &kmyapplication;. Never ever worry again about finding your best favorite photos again!
</para>


<sect1 id="what_is_kpb">
  <title>What is &kmyapplication;?</title>
  <para><emphasis>&kmyapplication;</emphasis> is a powerful, easy to use, intuitive and fast application to manage and organize all your digital photos. The main idea is to be able to annotate your photos with tags (labels) and to refind the photos using the given tags. The tags which can be created by yourself are arranged in a hierarchical tree.</para>
  <para>The <emphasis>&kmyapplication;</emphasis> GUI (graphical user interface) comes up with several points which make the handling with many photos very easy. This is just a short excerpt of it's goodies:</para>
  <itemizedlist>
    <listitem><para>Use several different types of tags in a highly configurable tag tree.</para></listitem>
    <listitem><para>Organize your photos from any source folder - they don't need to be in one and the same.</para></listitem>
    <listitem><para>Easily annotate tags to one or more images at a time.</para></listitem>
    <listitem><para>Quickly find images by the given tags.</para></listitem>
    <listitem><para>...</para></listitem>
  </itemizedlist>
</sect1>


<sect1 id="why_kpb">
  <title>Why &kmyapplication;?</title>
  <para>The idea for a photo managing program came up during September 2003. Having bought a digital camera a few months ago, the necessity for a program to manage all the taken photos became urgent. Without a program helping to organize hundreds or even thousands of photos is a very time consuming and not that easy task. We were looking for a program helping us to organize the photos in a smart way. It was important to us that such a program should not only help you storing your photos but also help you to refind them in a fast and easy way.</para>

  <para>When the idea came up to start with such a project, there were no other <emphasis>usable</emphasis> programs available doing that task in a fast and easy way. Neither free nor commercial products satisfied us. A few weeks after our "take off" KimDaBa 1.0 was released. We looked into this program but decided then to go on with the development of <emphasis>&kmyapplication;</emphasis>. KimDaBa was just not exactly what we were looking for. In February 2004 a first alpha-version of Fotoon was released. Fotoon came closer to what idea is... but not exactly either. We decided - once again - to go on working on <emphasis>&kmyapplication;</emphasis> but to have a close eye on these other applications.</para>

  <para>Yes, <emphasis>&kmyapplication;</emphasis> is another application for managing your photos. We know that there are - meanwhile - several programs to perform such tasks. Those applications promote themselves to make it easy handling thousands of photos. Having looked at some other applications, we found that it was not <emphasis>that</emphasis> easy and not nearly as straight forward as we think such an application should be.</para>

  <para>Digikam, another application for managing photos made a lot of progress while <emphasis>&kmyapplication;</emphasis> was in it's early development stages. As soon as people said they would like the tag function of Fotoon or <emphasis>&kmyapplication;</emphasis> Digikam implemented such a function as well. Well done, but not in the way we would like it. The Tag Tree of <emphasis>&kmyapplication;</emphasis> bring a much more powerful tool to manage your photos - give it a try!</para>

</sect1>

<sect1 id="feature_list">
  <title>Basic Feature List</title>
  <itemizedlist>
    <listitem><para>create a photo database with photos from several folders. These can be added single or recursively.</para></listitem>
    <listitem><para>annotate tags to the photos. This can be done for one photo only or for several photos at once.</para></listitem>
    <listitem><para>Use different kinds of tags: title, string, dates, numeric, option list and boolean. This will satisfy all your needs.</para></listitem>
    <listitem><para>search and filter the photos using any of the given tags.</para></listitem>
    <listitem><para>all pictures matching the chosen filter are displayed as thumbnails</para></listitem>
    <listitem><para>the pictures can be rotated (physically, EXIF or database only)</para></listitem>
    <listitem><para>show the EXIF informations of a selected file</para></listitem>
    <listitem><para>show the photos matching the filter or the selection in a slide show</para></listitem>
    <listitem><para>open the files with a any desired program</para></listitem>
    <listitem><para>export the photos matching the filter or the selection as symbolic links.</para></listitem>
    <listitem><para><emphasis>&kmyapplication;</emphasis>s look and feel is highly configurable.</para></listitem>
    <listitem><para>For a more complete feature and "to do" list, please visit the <emphasis>&kmyapplication;</emphasis> homepage.</para></listitem>
  </itemizedlist>
</sect1>

<sect1 id="evolution">
  <title>Evolution of <emphasis>&kmyapplication;</emphasis></title>
  <para>This is a quick overview of the evolution of <emphasis>&kmyapplication;</emphasis></para>

  <sect2>
    <title>Version 0.0.3</title>
    <para>Version 0.0.3 was the first release of <emphasis>&kmyapplication;</emphasis> and was released in February 2004. It did not provide many features but seemed quite stable already (probably because of the lack of features :-) ). The GUI provided a source folder tree and a main window in which thumbnails of the images in the imported folders were shown. There was also a tag tree - it was hard coded at this time. V0.0.3 already had the ability to alter the thumbnail size with a ruler.</para>
  </sect2>

  <sect2>
    <title>Version 0.0.4</title>
    <para>Version 0.0.4 was released in March 2004. Besides the features of Version 0.0.3, we provided a functional tag tree with title tags and boolean tags, improved filter abilities, a few new icons and a new tool bar.</para>
  </sect2>

  <sect2>
    <title>Version 0.0.5</title>
    <para>Released in April 2004. There are a lot of things to configure now and the GUI is cleaned up</para>
    <itemizedlist>
        <listitem><para>When setting filters on a parent tags, files associated with the sub tags are considered too. E.g. if dog is a sub tag of animal then, when searching for images containing an animal, the images tagged with dog must be displayed too.</para></listitem>
        <listitem><para>GUI mode is changeable between IDEAl and TabPage mode.</para></listitem>
        <listitem><para>Remember the selected files whenever possible (changing filter, changing preview size, ...).</para></listitem>
        <listitem><para>Set F5 as shortcut for "refresh view" not for "rescan filesystem".</para></listitem>
        <listitem><para>Ctrl+R as alternate shortcut for "refresh view".</para></listitem>
        <listitem><para>Use right mouse button on tag filters to cycle backwards through the options.</para></listitem>
        <listitem><para>The dock configuration is stored now. KDE is really great!</para></listitem>
        <listitem><para>...</para></listitem>
  </itemizedlist>
  </sect2>

  <sect2>
    <title>Version 0.0.6</title>
    <para>Released in June 2004.</para>
    <itemizedlist>
        <listitem><para>Tagging can be locked/unlocked now to avoid accidental change of tags. The lock can be unlocked temporary by holding the CTRL-key.</para></listitem>
        <listitem><para>The tree states (open/closed) nodes and the filters are stored.</para></listitem>
        <listitem><para>It is possible now to export selected/matching images as symbolic links to folders.</para></listitem>
        <listitem><para>Menu entries for showing/restoring the toolviews. It does not exactly what I did want, but the MDI (Toolview) API is a bit odd. But I think it works well enough.</para></listitem>
        <listitem><para>Add a quit action which closes all open window and exits KPhotoBook.</para></listitem>
        <listitem><para>Install a mimetype for KPhotoBook associating '*.kpb' files with KPhotoBook.</para></listitem>
    </itemizedlist>
  </sect2>

  <sect2>
    <title>Version 0.0.7</title>
    <para>Released in xxx 2005.</para>
    <itemizedlist>
        <listitem><para>version 0.0.7 is currently under construction</para></listitem>
    </itemizedlist>
  </sect2>

</sect1>

