    <sect2>
        <title>Selection mode</title>
        <para>The Thumbnail Window provides two different ways to select images. Chose the one you prefer.</para>
        <para>The "Extended selection mode" works like the selection in Konqueror. Select or deselect several images by using the SHIFT respectively CTRL key.</para>
        <para>The "Multi selection mode" works a bit different, You don't need to hold any key for selecting multiple images. Just click on one then on the next to select it too. You won't unselect the first one. To unselect a picture click on it a second time.</para>
    </sect2>

    <sect2>
        <title>Refresh the Thumbnail Window</title>
        <para>After having selected a filter you probably want to see what pictures match the filter selected. By pressing "F5", View --> Refresh View, or the icon in the toolbar you can refresh the thumbnails. <emphasis>&kmyapplication;</emphasis> will then find all the pictures you selected the tag and source filter for. If you want to automatically refresh the view after any change in the filter you can do so by the appropriate icon or via the Configure dialog.</para>
    </sect2>

    <sect2>
        <title>Open with external program</title>
        <para>Double-clicking on a thumbnail will open the photo in an external graphic viewer. The preferred graphic viewer can be set in the configure dialog.</para>
    </sect2>

</sect1>

<sect1 id="tags">
  <title>Tags</title>
      <para>Tags are the main tool to make the search functions of <emphasis>&kmyapplication;</emphasis> so powerful. They are a kind of label which can be given to the photos. You can add as many tags to a photo as you want to. They can be arranged in a tree (Tag Tree). There are also several types of tags which are explained later on.</para>
  <sect2>
    <title>Tag Tree</title>
    <para>Depending on your photo collection you probably need several tags to describe the content of all your photos. If you have many different kinds of photos you could easily lose yourself in all the tags you need. Therefore <emphasis>&kmyapplication;</emphasis> organizes the tags in a hierarchical structure - the Tag Tree. In the Tag Tree you can add new tags, deleted and edit them. You can also give every tag an icon which makes it easier to recognize it and work even faster. Through the Tag Tree you can attach tags to your photos but it can also figure as your filter. This all sounds a bit confusing but it is not. Read on...</para>
  </sect2>

  <sect2>
    <title>Adding, Deleting and Editing Tags</title>
    <para>The functions for adding, deleting and editing <emphasis>Tags</emphasis> can be reached by right clicking on the <emphasis>Tag Tree</emphasis>. Clicking on the background you can create <emphasis>Main Tags</emphasis>, clicking on a Tag you can create <emphasis>Sub Tags</emphasis>. <emphasis>Main Tags</emphasis> are there to let you give your tree a structure. You cannot associate a <emphasis>Main Tags</emphasis> with a photo nor can you filter for it. You can use any type of Tag as a <emphasis>Main Tags</emphasis>.</para>

    <sect3>
        <title>Adding Main Tags</title>
        <para>A Main Tag can be add through the menu "Manage" or via the context menu in the tag tree window. Make sure you do not right click on a already existing Tag there.</para>
        <para>As you can seen on the screenshot below, you can Give your Main Tag a Title, a comment and an Icon. If you do chose an icon, the text will be displayed anyway. Choosing no icon, no icon at all will be displayed. The comment will be shown as tooltip when hovering over the tag.</para>

